default11. This is a question for a user of IPCC 
defaultreports rather than an author.
default&#xa0;
defaultDoes the AR5 address the reliability of climate models?
default&#xa0;
default12. 
defaultThis question is so broad that almost any answer is possible. Yes, the IPCC does consider the reliability of climate models and finds they are much more reliable f
defaultor some variables (like global temperature) than others (like local precipitation). 
defaultIf the question is posed as “are the models reliable in all respects”, the answer is trivially “no”. 
defaultThe global coupled climate models that form the backbone of these asses
defaultsments are found to be consistently unreliable in their representation of extreme weather, which is the main reason we are unable to say more
default at present
default about human influence on weather extremes. 
default&#xa0;
defaultHas AR5 sufficiently explained the reasons behind the wide
defaultly reported hiatus in the global surface temperature record?
default&#xa0;
default13. The AR5 has demonstrated there are a number of possible reasons for the hiatus and concluded that there is insufficient evidence to attribute it to any specific cause. Temperature trends ove
defaultr a 15-year period have limited relevance to constraining long-term climate projections
default, and average temperatures over the past decade have been precisely in line with projections made back in the 1990s
default. That said, the fact that the very rapid warming betw
defaulteen the mid-1990s and the 
defaultfirst half of the
default 2000s 
defaulthas not continued does provide some evidence that the highest responses in the current generation of climate models are unrealistic, and this is reflected in the AR5 projections of near-term warming
default. It als
defaulto
default contributed 
defaultto 
default(although it was not the main factor
default in) 
defaultthe decision to reduce the lower bound of Equilibrium Climate Sensitivity to 1.5 degrees
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultDo the AR5 Physical Science Basis report’s conclusions strengthen or weaken the economic case for action to
default prevent dangerous climate change?
default&#xa0;
default14. 
defaultThe key conclusion that strengthens the case for some actions to prevent dangerous climate change is the fact that cumulative emissions of carbon dioxide emissions over the entire industrial epoch are the main determ
defaultinant of eventual warming, not emissions in any given year or commitment period. This highlights the importance of policies to address the long-term stock of fossil carbon, as opposed to measures to control the flow of greenhouse gas emissions that are the
default focus of 
defaultalmost all climate policies at present.
default 
default&#xa0;
default15. As an aside, it seems 
defaultstrange
default to ask about the economic implications of a report that is explicitly 
defaultand exclusively 
defaultfocused on Physical Science. 
defaultThis question might be more appropriate when the Assess
defaultments of Working Groups 2 and 3 are available.
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat implications do the IPCC’s conclusions in the AR5 Physical Science Basis report have for policy making both nationally and internationally?
default&#xa0;
default16. 
defaultBoth UK and international climate policy are exclusively f
defaultocused on reducing 
defaultthe flow of 
defaultemissions in the relatively short term, out to 2030 or so. This is resulting in a dangerous underinvestment in technologies like carbon capture and sequestration 
default(CCS) 
defaultthat are relatively expensive as short-term emission redu
defaultction measures. These technologies will
default, however,
default almost certainly be required eventually if we are to limit warming to two or even three degrees, given the overwhelming economic incentives to burn more fossil fuels than can be released into the atmosphere
default consistent with these temperature goals.
default&#xa0;
defaultIs the IPCC process an effective mechanism for a
defaultssessing scientific knowledge? Or has it focus
defaulted on providing a justification for political commitment?
default&#xa0;
default17. The response of 
defaultparticipants in 
defaultthe UNFCCC process 
defaultto 
defaultthe cumulative carbon budget conclusion is very instructive. Negotiators have been openly critical of the IPCC for what they see as an “unhelpful framing” of the problem. This illustrates that the IPCC is doing its job of highlighting important policy-rele
defaultvant science, not simply providing justification for any particular political decision.
