defaultIs the rate at which the UK Government intends to cut CO2 emissions appropriate in light of the findings of the IPCC AR5 Physical Scien
defaultce Basis report?
default&#xa0;
default19. The problem is not so much the rate as the manner of these reductions. 
defaultThe AR5 report highlights the critical importance of option value. 
defaultT
defaulthere has been no substantial reduction in the overall 
defaultuncer
defaulttainty in the climate response: 
defaultthe 
defaultincrease in the range of uncertainty in equilibrium climate sensitivity was appr
defaultoximately compensated for by a
default modest reduction in uncertaint
defaulty in 
defaultthe 
defaulttransient response. At the same time, the cumulative carbon budget demonstrates that, regardless of whethe
defaultr the response is at the high or low end of the current uncertainty range, emissions will eventually have to be reduced to zero if dangerous climate change is to be avoided. 
default&#xa0;
default20. 
defaultHence policies should focus on the development of technologies that would al
defaultlow rapid and substantial reductions in global emissions in the future, should they prove necessary
default. If this is
default at the expense of investment in short-term 
defaultemission reduction measures
default,
default which might ultimately prove 
defaultunnecessary
default if the response is at the low e
defaultnd of the current range
default, then so be it
default. 
default&#xa0;
default21. To put it bluntly, we 
defaultalready 
defaultknow the costs and externalities of wind power. 
defaultRapid deployment of wind power in the UK and Germany
default 
defaulttoday will therefore 
defaultmake 
defaultrelatively little difference 
defaultto the opt
defaultions we have a
defaultvailable for dealing with climate change on a global scale in the 2030s. 
defaultWe have much less idea about the relative merits of different CO2 geological storage options, which will take decades to evaluate. If temperatures reach 1.5 degrees and global emissio
defaultns are proving impossible to reduce through substitution measures, we are likely to need the option of deploying CCS on a very large-scale. The way things are going, we won’t have it, because we are 
defaultpouring subsidies into
default windmills instead. 
